{{refimprove||date=February 2013}} [[File:Самодельный магнитофон 1970ых.jpg|thumb|right|Tape recorder "Tembr" (1964) without casing (From museum of political history of Russia)]] '''''Magnitizdat''''' ({{lang-rus|магнитизда́т|p=məɡnʲɪtʲɪzˈdat}}, from the Russian words for "tape recorder" магнитофо́н {{IPA|[məɡnʲɪtɐˈfon]}}, and "publishing" изда́тельство {{IPA|[ɪˈzdatʲɪlʲstvə]}}<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Garey|2011|p=5}}</ref>) was the process of re-copying and self-distributing live [[Magnetic tape sound recording|audio tape]] recordings in the [[Soviet Union]] that were not available commercially. It is similar to [[bootleg recording]]s, except it was often sanctioned by the performers (who did not expect to make money from these recordings anyway) for the purpose of circumventing [[Censorship in the Soviet Union|Soviet political censorship]] and making their work as well known as possible.
The process of ''magnitizdat'' was less risky than publishing literature via [[samizdat]], since any person in the USSR was permitted to own a private [[Reel-to-reel audio tape recording|reel-to-reel]] tape recorder, while paper duplication equipment was under control of the state.
''Magnitizdat'' was the main method by which the songs of [[Bard (Soviet Union)|Russian bards]] such as [[Bulat Okudzhava]], [[Vladimir Vysotsky]] and [[Alexander Galich (writer)|Alexander Galich]] or [[punk bands]] like [[Grazhdanskaya Oborona]] made their way around the Soviet Union and abroad. Magnitizdat was also used to distribute lectures with anti-Soviet content.
